e: not Workflow because this behavior is about a single generation-quality decision, not a multi-step agentic pipeline outcome." ,"test_description":"Run against the real LLM with a fixed set of support questions and conversation contexts; score responses for question-answer relevance/off-topic rate with rubric checks, and fail when relevance drops below threshold.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"This test explicitly depends on live model output variability; lower levels cannot detect semantic quality regressions.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.82,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The tone re-check correctly identifies when a response is too formal for a casual-tier customer and triggers regeneration.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Slot A: \"tone re-check correctly identifies when a response is too formal ... and triggers regeneration.\" Slot B: model-output decision (tone judgment) governing branch/handoff. Slot C: if lowered to Integration, deterministic tone-check stubs can force \"too formal\" and miss failures where the real model misclassifies tone and never triggers regeneration. Final label: Agentic, because one real model decision controls orchestration correctness (Slot B), and stubs hide that failure mode (Slot C). Rejection-gate: not Workflow because the required assertion is the single gating decision plus trigger, not end-to-end quality across multiple agentic decisions." ,"test_description":"Provide casual-tier prompts likely to elicit formal drafts, run with real tone-check model enabled, and assert that overly formal first drafts are flagged and regeneration is actually invoked on those cases.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"The test requires real tone-classification behavior; a lower-level orchestration-only test would not validate \"correctly identifies.\"","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.14,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.7,